06360nam a22012615i 9780691231105DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912311057 a10.1515/97806912311052doi  a(DE-B1597)581237  a(OCoLC)1257324393  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a814.30992872221 aLoeffelholz, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom School to Salon :bReading Nineteenth-Century American Women's Poetry /cMary Loeffelholz. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b6 halftones. 2 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Objects of Recovery -- tI. Prodigy and Teacher; or, Poetry in the Domestic-Tutelary Complex -- tChapter One Who Killed Lucretia Davidson? -- tChapter Two The School of Lydia Sigourney -- tII. Lessons of the Sphinx: Poetry and Cultural Capital in Abolition and Reconstruction -- tChapter Three Poetry, Slavery, Personification: Maria Lowell's "Africa" -- tChapter Four A Difference in the Vernacular: The Reconstruction Poetry of Frances Ellen Watkins Harper -- tIII. The Conquest of Autonomy -- tChapter Five "Plied from Nought to Nought": Helen Hunt Jackson and the Field of Emily Dickinson's Refusals -- tChapter Six Metropolitan Pastoral: The Salon Poetry of Annie Fields -- tConclusion: The Sentiments of Recovery: Adrienne Rich and Nineteenth-Century Women's Culture -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the transformation and expansion of the nineteenth-century American literary canon in the past two decades, the work of the era's American women poets has come to be widely anthologized. But scant scholarship has arisen to make full sense of it. From School to Salon responds to this glaring gap. Mary Loeffelholz presents the work of nineteenth-century women poets in the context of the history, culture, and politics of the times. She uses a series of case studies to discuss why the recovery of nineteenth-century women's poetry has been a process of anthologization without succeeding analysis. At the same time, she provides a much-needed account of the changing social contexts through which nineteenth-century American women became poets: initially by reading, reciting, writing, and publishing poetry in school, and later, by doing those same things in literary salons, institutions created by the high-culture movement of the day. Along the way, Loeffelholz provides detailed analyses of the poetry, much of which has received little or no recent critical attention. She focuses on the works of a remarkably diverse array of poets, including Lucretia Maria Davidson, Lydia Sigourney, Maria Lowell, Frances Ellen Watkins Harper, Emily Dickinson, Helen Hunt Jackson, and Annie Fields. Impeccably researched and gracefully written, From School to Salon moves the study of nineteenth-century women's poetry to a new and momentous level.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican poetryxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAME Recorder.  aAmerican Revolution.  aAmherst College.  aBennett, Michael.  aBercovitch, Sacvan.  aBradstreet, Anne.  aBryant, William Cullen.  aBryn Mawr College.  aButler, Judith.  aCivil War, English.  aClark, Suzanne.  aCrain, Patricia.  aDayan, Joan.  aEmancipation Proclamation.  aFinch, Annie.  aFoucault, Michel.  aGliddon, George.  aGraham, Maryemma.  aHarper, Franc